            551
          ],
          "block_id": 0,
          "block_order": null
        },
        {
          "block_label": "figure_title",
          "block_content": "Figure 11-4. High-side Switching with an NPN BJT Driving a PNP BJT ",
          "block_bbox": [
            214,
            573,
            1562,
            623
          ],
          "block_id": 1,
          "block_order": null
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "Low-side switching (Recipe 11.1) is the most common and simplest arrangement,and unless you have a good reason such as the need for one end of the load to be connected to ground, you should use low-side switching.\n",
          "block_bbox": [
            208,
            689,
            1881,
            857
          ],
          "block_id": 2,
          "block_order": 1
        },
        {
          "block_label": "paragraph_title",
          "block_content": "See Also ",
          "block_bbox": [
            210,
            911,
            420,
            969
          ],
          "block_id": 3,
          "block_order": 2
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "For a discussion of NPN and PNP bipolar transistors, see Recipe 5.1.",
          "block_bbox": [
            209,
            1018,
            1553,
            1071
          ],
          "block_id": 4,
          "block_order": 3
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "GPIO portsand thir output logicare described in Reip10.7.",
          "block_bbox": [
            208,
            1105,
            1452,
            1155
          ],
          "block_id": 5,
          "block_order": 4
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "You will find an exampleof swiching withatransistorusinan Arduinoin Recipe 11.6 and for a Raspberry Pi in Recipe 11.7.\n",
          "block_bbox": [
            208,
            1193,
            1889,
            1301
          ],
          "block_id": 6,
          "block_order": 5
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "For switching using a MOSFET, see Recipe 11.3.",
          "block_bbox": [
            209,
            1341,
            1157,
            1391
          ],
          "block_id": 7,
          "block_order": 6
        },
        {
          "block_label": "paragraph_title",
          "block_content": "11.3 Switch Much More Power ",
          "block_bbox": [
            212,
            1457,
            1087,
            1525
          ],
          "block_id": 8,
          "block_order": 7
        },
        {
          "block_label": "paragraph_title",
          "block_content": "Problem ",
          "block_bbox": [
            211,
            1595,
            426,
            1651
          ],
          "block_id": 9,
          "block_order": 8
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "You want to allow a GPIO pin to control more power than it otherwise could, but a BJT isn't enough.\n",
          "block_bbox": [
            208,
            1694,
            1890,
            1808
          ],
          "block_id": 10,
          "block_order": 9
        },
        {
          "block_label": "paragraph_title",
          "block_content": "Solution ",
          "block_bbox": [
            211,
            1871,
            421,
            1926
          ],
          "block_id": 11,
          "block_order": 10
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "You can use a MOSFET as an electronic switch. Use the transistor in a commonsource arrangement.Figure 11-5 shows the schematicfor this circuit. Along with Recipe 11.1, you will find yourself using this circuit a lot.",
          "block_bbox": [
            207,
            1970,
            1891,
            2138
          ],
          "block_id": 12,
          "block_order": 11
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "This typeof switching is called\"low-side\"switching because the transistor acts as a switch between the low voltage of GND and the load.\n",
          "block_bbox": [
            207,
            2174,
            1888,
            2283
          ],
          "block_id": 13,
          "block_order": 12
        },
        {
          "block_label": "text",
          "block_content": "If the GPIOpinishigh(3.3Vor5V)andexceedsthegate-threholdvoltageof the MOSFET, theMOSFET will turn,llowincurrenttolwfrom+Vthrough the load to GND.\n",
          "block_bbox": [
            207,
            2317,
            1886,
            2491
          ],
          "block_id": 14,
          "block_order": 13
        },
        {
          "block_label": "footer",
          "block_content": "11.3 Switch Much More Power ",
          "block_bbox": [
            1330,
            2708,
            1749,
            2753
          ],
          "block_id": 15,
          "block_order": null
        },
        {
          "block_label": "number",
